div.p:

Brother Cosroe, I find myself much aggrieved
Yet insufficient to express the same; 
For it requires a great & thundering speech:

every life, complete, beat beating behind And the mounting image, the wind & [illeg.], still blow out the speech, even in the printed book. There is The It is crude. The poet is anonymous. This And yet what a All is now spoken by each actor. There are no abstractions. All is realised: the pomp & the masks & the great swollen figures; as if Nothing is left lurking in the shades. Still Even The figures are palpable, coloured, strident. Is it something has set in motion, not knights & ladies, but the crude, jagged outlines of real men. [And for?] there is a bombast & a splendour, the great painted wigs & their [illeg.] [logs?] are as still damp, un carved. Laughter, like great moths brought by the [illeg.]: But It is momentuous, [naked?]; resonant: And the great names clash like brass. Resound & [comedy?] No one is delicately depicted. There is no shadow: but all is gold & purple. And yet the [currency?], the trumpets, fill the words: the [abeard?], the huperbole (hyperbole): this is a mood, a splendid rhapsody: filled blown like a with [folio?], in their [hur?], in suffering; but yet – for there is no quarter, no stalling;
suddenly, in the stress of emotion; a another & yet, for all its stridency, its
pomp, all the height of splendour, how the poet can cut a gash in the fabric:
